===Etymology 1===
Shortened from {{m|en|hobby-horse}}, from {{der|en|enm|hoby}}, {{m|enm|hobyn}}, {{m|enm|hobin||small horse, pony}}, from {{der|en|fro|hobi}}, {{m|fro|*haubi}}, {{m|fro|haubby}}, {{m|fro|hobin}} {{gloss|"a nag, hobby"; > Modern French {{m|fro|aubin}}, Italian {{m|it|ubino}}}}, of {{der|en|gem|-}} origin: from {{der|en|fro|hober}}, {{m|fro|ober||to stir, move}}, from {{der|en|odt|hobben||to toss, move up and down}}; or from {{der|en|gmq|-}} origin related to {{cog|da|hoppe||a mare}}, {{cog|gmq-osw|hoppa||a young mare}}, {{cog|frr|hoppe||horse}}; both ultimately from {{der|en|gem-pro|*huppōną||to hop}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*kewb-||to bend; a bend, joint}}. More at {{l|en|hop}}, {{l|en|hobble}}.

The meaning of ''hobby-horse'' shifted from "small horse, pony" to "child's toy riding horse" to "favorite pastime or avocation" with the connecting notion being "activity that doesn't go anywhere". Possibly originally from a [[proper name]] for a horse, a diminutive of {{m|en|Robert}} or {{m|en|Robin}} (compare {{m|en|dobbin}}).

